<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-using-logarithms-to-compute-products-and-ratios" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Using Logarithms to Compute Products and Ratios</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_xs1a257m">
            <p xml:id="auto_ioc4eok9">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_ez1f9soj">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_wwhltjxo">
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_xr2goure">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_jsb41pxo">
                        1.2 Indices and Logarithms
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_3mrzkzgs">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_f2f91pwt">
                        Apply common logarithms in multiplication, division, powers and roots of numbers
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_fhdb7lxc" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_1nmiu5i4">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_em89d13u" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_a64htnnm">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_9wej8tin" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_rcpckjc9"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_2ahoi7l4">
                        <p xml:id="auto_44f7hs85">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand that logarithms convert multiplication to addition, division to subtraction, and powers/roots to multiplication/division of logarithms.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_wjikbmk0">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ef6kcxdz">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Use logarithm tables to perform multiplication, division, and find powers and roots of numbers.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_sj182mqo">
                        <p xml:id="auto_30jypw8o">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply logarithmic calculations to solve real-world problems involving areas, volumes, and compound calculations.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_93gkyh7y">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/indices-and-logarithms/using-logarithms-to-compute-products-and-ratios.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_opx79klx">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/indices-and-logarithms/step-by-step-guide_using-logarithms-to-compute-products-and-ratios.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery / Engage &amp; Explore</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_j9sciihc">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_0awkd653">
            <alert>Objective:</alert> To explore how logarithms simplify complex calculations.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_z2bz287t">
            <alert>Anchor Learning Experience: The Calculator Challenge</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_twwq4kog">
            <p xml:id="auto_ajyui5wu">
                Students work in groups.
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_9uz1ntv2">
                    <p xml:id="auto_suj31k4o">
                        In Part A, they try to compute <m>236.5 \times 42.8</m>, <m>528.6 \div 24.7</m>, and <m>\sqrt[3]{524.8}</m> without using a calculator. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6jl3mqb7">
                    <p xml:id="auto_szhu8o51">
                        In Part B, they use logarithm tables to find <m>\log(236.5)</m> and <m>\log(42.8)</m>, and discover what happens when they add these two logarithms and find the antilog of the sum. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_825qni2n">
            <alert>Discussion Questions:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_v0i3s14i"><p xml:id="auto_bjyfddbs">How does adding logarithms relate to multiplication?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ewll8yvr"><p xml:id="auto_wt43t3m0">How does subtracting logarithms relate to division?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qcq18tic"><p xml:id="auto_5r8t9uqx">What operation on logarithms gives you a power?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ghvy05jm"><p xml:id="auto_ce473xo9">What operation on logarithms gives you a root?</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_6j5j48ja">
            <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> Circulate among groups, asking probing questions. Guide students to discover that <m>\log(a \times b) = \log(a) + \log(b)</m> and <m>\log(a \div b) = \log(a) - \log(b)</m>. Use student discoveries to bridge to formal instruction.
        </p>
    </axiom>




    <activity xml:id="act-calculator-challenge">
        <title>The Calculator Challenge</title>
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_8im4v4hs">Work in groups to explore the following challenge.</p>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Part A: The Long Way</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_mcntm93x">Without using a calculator, try to compute:</p>
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_tpacf43j"><p xml:id="auto_2yop5x66"><m>236.5 \times 42.8</m></p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ku16w7mm"><p xml:id="auto_uh4bmqbx"><m>528.6 \div 24.7</m></p></li>
                    <!-- <li xml:id="auto_82n2lkcw"><p xml:id="auto_gmnh6gsk"><m>\sqrt[3]{524.8}</m></p></li> -->
                </ol>
            </paragraphs>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Part B: Discovering the Pattern</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_m7bewk5e">Use your logarithm tables to find:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_6nk7r50u"><p xml:id="auto_4s37i6r2"><m>\log(236.5)</m></p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_orrovpx8"><p xml:id="auto_sw7gla9l"><m>\log(42.8)</m></p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_satn41ki"><p xml:id="auto_xq7kvten">What do you notice when you add these two logarithms?</p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_9z4y1fm0"><p xml:id="auto_p8umxu03">What happens when you find the antilog of the sum?</p></li>
                </ul>
            </paragraphs>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Discussion Questions</title>
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_hxl8o1k2"><p xml:id="auto_q3t1qq49">How does adding logarithms relate to multiplication?</p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_lz3wj5p3"><p xml:id="auto_vbxqxypc">How does subtracting logarithms relate to division?</p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_eg3bvk1l"><p xml:id="auto_a0p1zsh2">What operation on logarithms gives you a power?</p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_xto5pqzz"><p xml:id="auto_ut2eg6nj">What operation on logarithms gives you a root?</p></li>
                </ol>
            </paragraphs>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <insight xml:id="ins-multiplicative-log-laws">
        <title>Multiplicative Laws of Logarithms</title>
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_cagc6n64">The main laws used for calculations are:</p>
            <ol>
                <li xml:id="auto_pcf6a2gz"><p xml:id="auto_tupz4k1p"><m>\log(ab)=\log a+\log b</m> — Product Law (multiply by adding logs)</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ypu2uei1"><p xml:id="auto_obkpgkhx"><m>\log(a/b)=\log a-\log b</m> — Quotient Law (divide by subtracting logs)</p></li>
                <!-- <li xml:id="auto_qxmvbx6l"><p xml:id="auto_u1lwws4o"><m>\log(a^n)=n\log a</m> — Power Law (powers become multipliers)</p></li> -->
                <!-- <li xml:id="auto_8914d61k"><p xml:id="auto_c5et3197"><m>\log(\sqrt[n]{a})=\tfrac{1}{n}\log a</m> — Root Law (roots divide the log)</p></li> -->
            </ol>
            <p xml:id="auto_dnx5pddl">The general process: find the logs, apply the operation (+, −, ×, ÷ on logs), then find the antilog of the result.</p>
            <p xml:id="auto_s8bbid9p"><em>Misconception:</em> <strong>log(a+b) ≠ log a + log b</strong>. The laws only apply to multiplication, division, powers and roots.</p>
        </statement>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction / Explain</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_qsp457bb">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_onhnvfec">
            <alert>Objective:</alert> To formalize the laws of logarithms for multiplication, division, powers, and roots.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_arbk3mpl">
            <alert>Key Takeaways — The Four Laws of Logarithms for Calculations:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_i8bbnb5u">
            1. <alert>Product Law (Multiplication):</alert> <m>\log(a \times b) = \log(a) + \log(b)</m>. To multiply: ADD the logarithms, then find antilog.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_swwy65ln">
            2. <alert>Quotient Law (Division):</alert> <m>\log(a \div b) = \log(a) - \log(b)</m>. To divide: SUBTRACT the logarithms, then find antilog.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_cvbyge3i">
            3. <alert>Power Law:</alert> <m>\log(a^b) = b \times \log(a)</m>. To find a power: MULTIPLY the logarithm by the exponent, then find antilog.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ewmkjubv">
            4. <alert>Root Law:</alert> <m>\log(\sqrt[n]{a}) = \frac{1}{n} \times \log(a)</m>. To find a root: DIVIDE the logarithm by the root index, then find antilog.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_tp3h9f12">
            <alert>The General Process:</alert> Step 1: Find <m>\log</m> of each number from tables. Step 2: Apply the appropriate operation (+, −, ×, ÷). Step 3: Find antilog of the result.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_diwq9eac">
            <alert>Addressing Misconceptions:</alert> <q>Remember: <m>\log(a + b) \neq \log(a) + \log(b)</m>. The laws only work for multiplication, division, powers, and roots — NOT for addition or subtraction!</q>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="ex-multiplication-using-logs">
        <title>Multiplication using Logarithms</title>
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_i9szyadv">Find <m>236.5 \times 42.8</m> using logarithm tables.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_kogm0sdx">Step 1: From tables, <m>\log(236.5)=2.3741</m> and <m>\log(42.8)=1.6318</m>.</p>
            <p xml:id="auto_l51hg83u">Step 2: Add the logs: <m>2.3741+1.6318=4.0059</m>.</p>
            <p xml:id="auto_zfqmettq">Step 3: Antilog of <m>4.0059</m> gives <m>\approx 10\,160</m>, so <m>236.5\times42.8\approx10\,160</m>.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-division-using-logs">
        <title>Division using Logarithms</title>
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_athze6m6">Find <m>528.6 \div 24.7</m> using logarithm tables.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_80fv030l">Step 1: From tables, <m>\log(528.6)=2.7233</m> and <m>\log(24.7)=1.3927</m>.</p>
            <p xml:id="auto_1llbekd3">Step 2: Subtract the logs: <m>2.7233-1.3927=1.3306</m>.</p>
            <p xml:id="auto_vd4xufrv">Step 3: Antilog of <m>1.3306</m> gives <m>\approx 21.4</m>, so <m>528.6\div24.7\approx21.4</m>.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

